About the safeguards
I've introduced.

86
00:04:57,040 --> 00:04:59,679
My newbureaucratic
watchdog office, for instance.

87
00:04:59,920 --> 00:05:03,230
It sounds as if we'll need a pack
of watchdogs before very long.

88
00:05:03,400 --> 00:05:04,799
But thank you very much.

89
00:05:05,720 --> 00:05:06,994
In next week's topic...

90
00:05:07,160 --> 00:05:09,833
- Howwas I?
- Splendid, Minister.

91
00:05:10,440 --> 00:05:12,351
Very dignified. Very suitable.

92
00:05:12,520 --> 00:05:14,590
Yes, Sir Humphrey,
I congratulate you.

93
00:05:14,760 --> 00:05:16,751
Jim is nowperfectly
house trained.

94
00:05:16,920 --> 00:05:18,638
He does exactly
what you tell him.

95
00:05:18,800 --> 00:05:21,394
- If you'll excuse me, Mr. Weasel.
- Weisel.

96
00:05:23,480 --> 00:05:26,631
You say everything the Civil Service
programmes you to say.

97
00:05:26,880 --> 00:05:28,552
What are you a man ora mouth?

98
00:05:28,720 --> 00:05:30,073
Very amusing, Frank.

99
00:05:30,240 --> 00:05:33,357
It might be hard fora Political
Advisorto understand this,

100
00:05:33,520 --> 00:05:35,431
but I am merely a Civil Servant,

101
00:05:35,600 --> 00:05:38,831
I simply do as I am instructed
by my master.

102
00:05:39,120 --> 00:05:41,429
If the Minister's a woman
what do you call her?

103
00:05:41,680 --> 00:05:43,432
Yes, that's rather interesting.

104
00:05:43,600 --> 00:05:44,999
We sought an answer

105
00:05:45,160 --> 00:05:48,755
when I was Principal Private Secretary
and Dr. Edith Summerskill,

106
00:05:48,920 --> 00:05:51,912
as she then was,
was appointed Minister in 1947.

107
00:05:52,080 --> 00:05:54,913
I didn't quite like to refer
to heras my Mistress.

108
00:05:55,960 --> 00:05:58,713
- Whatwas the answer?
- We're still waiting for it.

109
00:05:59,520 --> 00:06:02,671
It's underreview, is it?
Rome wasn't built in a day.

110
00:06:02,840 --> 00:06:05,070
- These things take time.
- I must be going.

111
00:06:05,240 --> 00:06:07,231
- Me too.
- May I remind you

112
00:06:07,400 --> 00:06:09,516
we meet tomorrowmorning
at Paddington at 8?

113
00:06:09,680 --> 00:06:11,955
- Where are we going?
- Swansea, Minister.

114
00:06:12,120 --> 00:06:15,908
You're addressing the Conference
of Municipal Treasurers.

115
00:06:16,080 --> 00:06:17,195
Oh, yes.

116
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:20,591
You're due in Newcastle
to address the by election meeting.

117
00:06:20,760 --> 00:06:22,478
- So I am.
- You can't do both.

118
00:06:22,640 --> 00:06:24,790
- I can't do both.
- That's a Civil Service junket.

119
00:06:24,960 --> 00:06:27,474
- The by election's important.
- It's important.

120
00:06:27,640 --> 00:06:31,076
The Conference is in yourdiary.
They expect you in Swansea.

121
00:06:31,240 --> 00:06:33,071
They expects you in Newcastle.

122
00:06:33,240 --> 00:06:35,834
- How come he's double booked?
- How come I'm double booked?

123
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:38,673
Well, largely because nobody
told me about Newcastle.

124
00:06:38,840 --> 00:06:40,558
- Why didn't you tell him?
- Why didn't you?

125
00:06:40,720 --> 00:06:42,278
I can't remembereverything.

126
00:06:43,320 --> 00:06:45,311
Frank, I think
I'd bettergo to Swansea.

127
00:06:45,480 --> 00:06:47,596
- Is that a decision?
- Yes, that's final.

128
00:06:47,760 --> 00:06:49,318
The P. M. Expects you
to go to Newcastle.

129
00:06:49,480 --> 00:06:50,674
The P. M?

130
00:06:50,960 --> 00:06:53,155
I think I'd bettergo
to Newcastle, Bernard.

131
00:06:53,880 --> 00:06:56,440
- Is that a decision, Jim?
- Yes, that's final.

132
00:06:56,600 --> 00:06:58,431
- Now I'm going home.
- Is that a decision?

133
00:06:58,600 --> 00:06:59,953
No, quite seriously...

134
00:07:00,200 --> 00:07:02,475
I think you've made
the wrong decision.

135
00:07:02,640 --> 00:07:04,949
Yourvisit to Swansea's
been announced.

136
00:07:05,120 --> 00:07:07,350
- You can't get out of it.
- Oh, Lord!

137
00:07:07,520 --> 00:07:10,751
Find a way of getting me
from Swansea to Newcastle.

138
00:07:10,920 --> 00:07:14,151
Car, train, helicopter, anything.
I'll have to do both.

139
00:07:14,320 --> 00:07:16,709
And now I'm going home,
and that is final!

140
00:07:16,880 --> 00:07:18,996
- Finallyfinal?
- Absolutelyfinally.

141
00:07:19,520 --> 00:07:22,034
If you could do
all yourboxes tonight.

142
00:07:22,200 --> 00:07:26,034
There's all the M&A Committee
papers and all the letters.

143
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:28,316
And if you're a good boy,
you'll get a sweetie.

144
00:07:28,480 --> 00:07:29,480
Good.

145
00:07:35,960 --> 00:07:37,154
Hello, darling.

146
00:07:38,320 --> 00:07:41,118
- Thanks, George. Goodnight.
- Goodnight, sir.

147
00:07:44,960 --> 00:07:46,757
- Hello, darling.
- Hello.

148
00:07:48,760 --> 00:07:50,159
Leaving me at last?

149
00:07:50,320 --> 00:07:52,595
It's ouranniversary tomorrow,
have you forgotten?

150
00:07:52,760 --> 00:07:55,069
No, of course I haven't forgotten.

151
00:07:55,760 --> 00:07:58,069
We're going to Paris.
Oh, my God!

152
00:07:58,240 --> 00:07:59,753
- You had forgotten.
- No, I hadn't.

153
00:07:59,920 --> 00:08:02,798
No, it's just that I...
I didn't... I'm double...

154
00:08:03,200 --> 00:08:05,589
- I'm going to Swansea tomorrow.
- Swansea?

155
00:08:05,760 --> 00:08:06,829
And Newcastle.

156
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:08,991
I don'twant to go there
formy anniversary.

157
00:08:09,160 --> 00:08:10,752
No. Not you. Just me.

158
00:08:10,920 --> 00:08:12,876
- Cancel them!
- I can't.

159
00:08:18,200 --> 00:08:19,553
What are you doing?

160
00:08:21,400 --> 00:08:23,789
Cancel them! We booked this
three months ago.

161
00:08:24,040 --> 00:08:26,952
- I can't.
- Then I'll go to Paris without you.

162
00:08:32,440 --> 00:08:34,670
Hello, Bernard...
Yes, it's me...

163
00:08:34,840 --> 00:08:36,956
I'm going to have
to cancel tomorrow.

164
00:08:37,840 --> 00:08:40,035
Swansea and Newcastle.

165
00:08:41,120 --> 00:08:43,588
It's my wife's wedding
anniversary tomorrow...

166
00:08:44,800 --> 00:08:45,949
It's yours too!

167
00:08:46,120 --> 00:08:49,237
Yeah, and mine too actually.
Yes, it is.

168
00:08:49,720 --> 00:08:51,631
Coincidence?
Don't be silly.

169
00:08:52,120 --> 00:08:54,793
Anyway, I'm going to Paris
tomorrow and that's final.

170
00:08:55,480 --> 00:08:58,870
Yes, I said that before,
but this time is final!

171
00:08:59,960 --> 00:09:02,520
You'll just have to cope
as best as you can.

172
00:09:03,600 --> 00:09:04,669
Yes?

173
00:09:05,320 --> 00:09:07,231
Yes... definitely...

174
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:09,319
Yes...

175
00:09:09,520 --> 00:09:10,748
Is that clear?

176
00:09:11,320 --> 00:09:12,435
Right!

177
00:09:12,880 --> 00:09:14,393
We're going to Paris.

178
00:09:14,680 --> 00:09:17,069
No, I'm going to Swansea
and Newcastle.

179
00:09:21,600 --> 00:09:24,194
- See me on TV tonight?
- I saw somebody who looked like you.

180
00:09:24,360 --> 00:09:26,191
- What's that meant to mean?
- Nothing.

181
00:09:26,360 --> 00:09:29,079
Frank says I've become
a Civil Service mouthpiece.

182
00:09:29,240 --> 00:09:30,434
- Yes.
- What do you mean, yes?

183
00:09:30,600 --> 00:09:32,431
- Well... yes.
- You mean you agree?

184
00:09:32,600 --> 00:09:35,034
- Of course.
- What do you mean, of course?

185
00:09:35,200 --> 00:09:38,510
You could have hired and actor
to say it all foryou.

186
00:09:38,680 --> 00:09:41,148
And why not just sign
your letters with a rubberstamp?

187
00:09:41,320 --> 00:09:43,709
Orget an Assistant Principal
to sign them foryou.

188
00:09:43,880 --> 00:09:45,279
They write them anyway.

189
00:09:45,600 --> 00:09:48,398
Assistant Principals
do notwrite my letters!

190
00:09:49,280 --> 00:09:50,998
UnderSecretaries do that.

191
00:09:51,480 --> 00:09:53,391
I rest my case, my lord.

192
00:09:54,320 --> 00:09:57,710
- You think I've become a puppet?
- Yes, I do.

193
00:09:57,920 --> 00:10:00,832
Get Miss Piggy to do yourjob.
She's prettier.

194
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:02,592
I don't knowwhat to do.

195
00:10:02,760 --> 00:10:04,910
I'm just swamped by the work.

196
00:10:05,600 --> 00:10:07,397
Oh, Annie, I'm so depressed.

197
00:10:09,400 --> 00:10:11,516
As we're not going to Paris,

198
00:10:11,640 --> 00:10:15,428
let's at least go out
fora quiet little dinnertonight.

199
00:10:16,120 --> 00:10:17,235
No, I can't.

200
00:10:17,400 --> 00:10:19,914
Bernard's told me
to get through three boxes.

201
00:10:20,080 --> 00:10:22,036
What do you mean,
Bernard's told you?

202
00:10:22,240 --> 00:10:25,038
When you edited "Reform"
you were quite different.

203
00:10:25,200 --> 00:10:27,475
You went in,
you told people what to do,

204
00:10:27,640 --> 00:10:29,358
and you got what you wanted!

205
00:10:29,520 --> 00:10:32,671
Eitheryou get them by the throat
orthey get you by the throat!

206
00:10:32,840 --> 00:10:36,116
Howmany articles
did you tearup in those days?

207
00:10:36,280 --> 00:10:39,317
- Dozens.
- And howmany official papers?

208
00:10:39,560 --> 00:10:42,313
- I'm not allowed to!
- Not allowed to?

209
00:10:42,560 --> 00:10:46,439
Darling, you're the Minister,
you can do anything you like.

210
00:10:50,600 --> 00:10:52,795
No, Humphrey, I've decided
that Frank was right.

211
00:10:52,960 --> 00:10:54,234
And Bob McKenzie too.

212
00:10:54,400 --> 00:10:57,039
The National Data Base has got
to be organised differently.

213
00:10:57,200 --> 00:10:58,200
Yes, Minister.

214
00:10:58,360 --> 00:11:00,396
We want all possible
built in safeguards.

215
00:11:00,560 --> 00:11:02,551
- Yes, Minister.
- Right away.

216
00:11:02,720 --> 00:11:05,632
What precisely do you mean,
right away?

217
00:11:06,480 --> 00:11:07,913
I mean right away.

218
00:11:08,440 --> 00:11:10,431
I see, you mean right away?

219
00:11:10,920 --> 00:11:13,434
- Got it in one, Humphrey.
- Well, Minister...

220
00:11:13,600 --> 00:11:16,273
We are still in the early months
of this Government.

221
00:11:16,440 --> 00:11:17,919
And there's an awful lot to get...

222
00:11:18,080 --> 00:11:20,150
The Data Base rules
have got to be changed. Now!

223
00:11:20,320 --> 00:11:23,630
- But you can't, Minister.
- Yes, I can, I'm the Minister.

224
00:11:23,840 --> 00:11:25,512
Yes, indeed you are, Minister.

225
00:11:26,240 --> 00:11:28,356
And quite
an excellent Ministerat that.

226
00:11:28,520 --> 00:11:30,511
Nevermind the soft soap,
Humphrey.

227
00:11:30,720 --> 00:11:34,030
I want all citizens to have a right
to see theirown files

228
00:11:34,200 --> 00:11:37,875
and I want legislation to make
unauthorised access, illegal.

229
00:11:38,440 --> 00:11:40,829
- Very well. It shall be done.
- Good.

230
00:11:41,120 --> 00:11:44,396
But the legislation necessary
to give the public the right

231
00:11:44,560 --> 00:11:47,870
to take legal action
is extremely complicated

232
00:11:48,040 --> 00:11:51,077
and would take
considerable time to draft,

233
00:11:51,240 --> 00:11:52,798
promulgate and enact.

234
00:11:52,960 --> 00:11:56,555
Legislation isn't necessaryfora
citizen to see his own files, is it?

235
00:11:56,920 --> 00:11:59,388
- No...
- Then, we'll startwith that.

236
00:11:59,560 --> 00:12:02,836
I suppose we could manage that
slightly quicker,

237
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:06,310
but there's an awful lot of
administrative problems as well.

238
00:12:06,480 --> 00:12:08,391
This must have been
examined before.

239
00:12:08,560 --> 00:12:11,393
The Data Base has been
in preparation foryears.

240
00:12:11,560 --> 00:12:14,199
There must have been
discussions about it.

241
00:12:14,360 --> 00:12:17,272
- Yes, indeed.
- What conclusions were reached?

242
00:12:19,960 --> 00:12:22,758
Humphrey, what conclusions
were reached?

243
00:12:24,040 --> 00:12:26,998
What did my predecessor
want to do about it?

