00:12:27,280 --> 00:12:29,316
Humphrey, can you hearme?

245
00:12:30,960 --> 00:12:32,473
My lips are sealed.

246
00:12:33,240 --> 00:12:34,309
I beg yourpardon?

247
00:12:34,480 --> 00:12:37,438
I am not at liberty to reveal
previous plans, Minister.

248
00:12:37,600 --> 00:12:38,669
Why not?

249
00:12:38,840 --> 00:12:42,435
Would you like everything that
you have said in this office

250
00:12:42,600 --> 00:12:45,558
to be revealed subsequently
to one of youropponents?

251
00:12:46,600 --> 00:12:47,715
I see. No.

252
00:12:47,880 --> 00:12:51,714
We cannot give youropponents
political ammunition against you.

253
00:12:51,960 --> 00:12:53,951
But Tom Sargent
was my predecessor.

254
00:12:54,120 --> 00:12:56,680
It isn't a party
political mattersurely?

255
00:12:56,840 --> 00:12:59,434
It's a matterof principle.
It justwouldn't be...

256
00:12:59,600 --> 00:13:03,513
I see and we don'twant
to do anything thatwouldn't be...

257
00:13:03,680 --> 00:13:04,715
No.

258
00:13:06,200 --> 00:13:08,350
- Oh, excuse me, Minister.
- Yes, Bernard?

259
00:13:08,520 --> 00:13:10,078
A slight problem, Minister.

260
00:13:10,440 --> 00:13:12,237
Because of the adverse...

261
00:13:12,400 --> 00:13:16,313
not entirelyfavourable press
reaction to your interview,

262
00:13:16,480 --> 00:13:19,199
the otherChannel wants you
fortheirprogramme.

263
00:13:19,360 --> 00:13:20,509
- Say no.
- No?

264
00:13:20,680 --> 00:13:22,113
- Yes, no.
- Yes no?

265
00:13:23,200 --> 00:13:26,112
- Yes, say no! That's final.
- If that's what you want.

266
00:13:26,280 --> 00:13:28,589
But they would go ahead
with the item

267
00:13:28,760 --> 00:13:31,513
and nobody would be there
to state yourcase.

268
00:13:31,680 --> 00:13:32,999
No? Okay, yes.

269
00:13:33,360 --> 00:13:34,793
No, okay, yes...

270
00:13:36,080 --> 00:13:38,071
- Oh, I see what you mean.
- Yes.

271
00:13:38,280 --> 00:13:39,599
Finallyfinal?

272
00:13:40,200 --> 00:13:41,679
Thank you, Bernard.

273
00:13:42,880 --> 00:13:46,031
What am I going to tell them
about safeguards. Humphrey?

274
00:13:46,200 --> 00:13:48,760
Perhaps you could
remind them, Minister,

275
00:13:48,920 --> 00:13:51,115
that Rome wasn't built in a day?

276
00:14:01,440 --> 00:14:02,589
Tom.

277
00:14:03,320 --> 00:14:05,834
- Oh, my dearfellow.
- Mind if I join you?

278
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:07,319
No, of course not.

279
00:14:07,840 --> 00:14:11,389
Well, how are you enjoying
being in opposition?

280
00:14:11,840 --> 00:14:13,671
How are you enjoying
being in Government?

281
00:14:13,840 --> 00:14:16,752
Well, not as much as I expected,
actually.

282
00:14:16,920 --> 00:14:20,071
- Well, not at the moment.
- Humphrey got you undercontrol?

283
00:14:20,360 --> 00:14:22,191
It's so hard to get things done.

284
00:14:22,360 --> 00:14:25,158
- Did you manage to get things done?
- Oh, almost nothing.

285
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:30,391
When I did cotton on to his technique,
there was the election.

286
00:14:30,600 --> 00:14:33,751
- Technique?
- Stalling technique.

287
00:14:34,280 --> 00:14:36,874
- Stalling technique?
- It comes in five stages.

288
00:14:37,360 --> 00:14:41,717
First, he'll tell you there's lots
of things to be getting on with.

289
00:14:41,920 --> 00:14:44,115
- He told me that this morning.
- Quite.

290
00:14:44,600 --> 00:14:47,512
Then, if you still persist,
he'll say something like

291
00:14:47,680 --> 00:14:50,877
"Ah, yes, Minister,
I quite appreciate the intention,

292
00:14:51,040 --> 00:14:52,996
certainly something
ought to be done,

293
00:14:53,160 --> 00:14:56,277
but are you sure this is
the rightway to achieve it?".

294
00:14:56,440 --> 00:14:57,873
I must make a note of this.

295
00:14:58,040 --> 00:15:01,476
Now, if you are still undeterred,
he will shift his ground.

296
00:15:01,760 --> 00:15:04,558
He will shift from telling you
how to do it

297
00:15:04,720 --> 00:15:06,472
to when you should do it.

298
00:15:06,680 --> 00:15:08,113
I mean, he'll say,

299
00:15:08,520 --> 00:15:13,640
"Now, Minister, this is not the right time,
forall sorts of reasons".

300
00:15:13,800 --> 00:15:16,553
- And Ministers settle forthat?
- Well, lots do.

301
00:15:16,720 --> 00:15:20,633
And if you don't, he'll say that
the policy"has run into difficulties".

302
00:15:20,800 --> 00:15:24,759
- Such as?
- Technical, political, legal...

303
00:15:25,520 --> 00:15:27,158
Legal are the best sort.

304
00:15:27,320 --> 00:15:29,959
He can make those
totally incomprehensible.

305
00:15:30,320 --> 00:15:34,279
And with any luck, this technique
will have lasted forthree years

306
00:15:34,440 --> 00:15:37,000
and you'll be at the final stage
when he says:

307
00:15:37,160 --> 00:15:39,913
"We're getting very close
to the next general election.

308
00:15:40,080 --> 00:15:42,071
Are you sure you can get
this policy through?"

309
00:15:42,240 --> 00:15:44,196
Howhas it taken three years?

310
00:15:44,360 --> 00:15:47,796
Sir Humphrey will do absolutely
nothing unless you chase him.

311
00:15:47,960 --> 00:15:49,871
And you've got
fartoo much to do.

312
00:15:50,040 --> 00:15:53,589
You see, it's what they call
"creative inertia".

313
00:15:55,960 --> 00:15:58,997
What's the policy you're trying
to get through anyway?

314
00:15:59,160 --> 00:16:02,118
I'm trying to make
this National Integrated Data Base

315
00:16:02,280 --> 00:16:03,952
a bit less of a Big Brother.

316
00:16:05,640 --> 00:16:07,392
Oh, is that what it is?

317
00:16:07,560 --> 00:16:10,358
- He's told you it's all quite new?
- Well, yes.

318
00:16:10,520 --> 00:16:12,636
My dearfellow,
we spent years on that.

319
00:16:12,800 --> 00:16:15,268
We had a White Paper
when they called election.

320
00:16:15,440 --> 00:16:16,759
I've done it all.

321
00:16:17,400 --> 00:16:20,278
- And administrative problems?
- I've solved them.

322
00:16:20,760 --> 00:16:23,274
And you couldn't see
any of the previous papers?

323
00:16:23,440 --> 00:16:25,635
No wonder.
He's wiped the slate clean.

324
00:16:26,640 --> 00:16:29,473
D'you knowwhat his next move's
gonna be?

325
00:16:29,640 --> 00:16:32,313
- No.
- Howmany boxes have you got?

326
00:16:32,480 --> 00:16:34,630
- Three? Four?
- Five.

327
00:16:34,800 --> 00:16:37,439
Did he tell you not to worry
about the fifth one?

328
00:16:37,680 --> 00:16:40,114
- Yes.
- Right. I'll take a bet.

329
00:16:40,280 --> 00:16:43,192
You will find at the bottom
of the fifth box a memo

330
00:16:43,360 --> 00:16:47,194
which explains exactly why
any newmoves on the Data Base

331
00:16:47,360 --> 00:16:49,476
must be delayed.
If you don't find it,

332
00:16:49,640 --> 00:16:52,837
he won't do anotherblind thing,
but in six month's time

333
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:56,788
he'll say that he has told you
all about it.

334
00:16:57,440 --> 00:17:01,035
Tom, you were in office foryears.
You know all the Civil Service tricks.

335
00:17:01,200 --> 00:17:03,839
Not all, old boy.
Just a fewhundred.

336
00:17:04,840 --> 00:17:08,913
And how do you make them do
something they don'twant to do?

337
00:17:09,440 --> 00:17:13,831
My dearfellow, if I knew that
I wouldn't be in Opposition.

338
00:17:17,080 --> 00:17:19,992
But I don't get it.
Tom's the opposition.

339
00:17:20,160 --> 00:17:21,798
Why did he tell you all this?

340
00:17:21,960 --> 00:17:25,475
- The Opposition aren't the opposition.
- Of course not. Silly of me.

341
00:17:25,640 --> 00:17:28,757
- They are called that.
- They're the opposition in exile.

342
00:17:29,720 --> 00:17:32,473
The Civil Service are
the Opposition in residence.

343
00:17:33,160 --> 00:17:36,869
Now then, bottom of the fifth box,
Tom said.

344
00:17:37,040 --> 00:17:39,998
But you can't really do anything.

345
00:17:40,160 --> 00:17:41,309
Oh, can't I?

346
00:17:41,520 --> 00:17:43,954
Tom's given me all his papers
on the Data Base.

347
00:17:44,640 --> 00:17:46,198
Three year's worth!

348
00:17:46,520 --> 00:17:47,748
Marvellous!

349
00:17:50,320 --> 00:17:51,833
Found it.

350
00:17:52,560 --> 00:17:54,835
It had slipped
into an 80 page report

351
00:17:55,000 --> 00:17:56,752
on Welfare procedures.

352
00:17:58,880 --> 00:18:01,269
"Safeguards
still underdiscussion...

353
00:18:02,240 --> 00:18:04,196
programme not finalised...

354
00:18:04,760 --> 00:18:06,398
nothing precipitate...

355
00:18:06,880 --> 00:18:11,112
failing instructions to the contrary,
propose await developments".

356
00:18:11,280 --> 00:18:12,280
Typical!

357
00:18:12,440 --> 00:18:15,989
- Ring Humphrey and tell him.
- I'll see him first thing.

358
00:18:16,280 --> 00:18:18,999
- Ring him now!
- It's two o'clock.

359
00:18:19,160 --> 00:18:21,515
- He'll be fast asleep.
- Exactly!

360
00:18:23,760 --> 00:18:24,795
Annie.

361
00:18:24,960 --> 00:18:27,315
Why should he be asleep
and you're still working?

362
00:18:27,480 --> 00:18:29,789
He's had you on the run.
Now it's yourturn.

363
00:18:30,680 --> 00:18:32,477
I couldn't do that.

364
00:18:33,440 --> 00:18:34,668
What's his number?

365
00:18:35,960 --> 00:18:39,157
Itwas in the fifth box,
you couldn't have got to it earlier.

366
00:18:39,360 --> 00:18:40,509
True.

367
00:18:58,080 --> 00:18:59,080
Yes?

368
00:18:59,240 --> 00:19:01,834
Humphrey,
sorry to ring you so late.

369
00:19:02,240 --> 00:19:05,471
I didn't interrupt you
in the middle of dinner, did I?

370
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:09,195
No, we finished dinner
some while ago.

371
00:19:09,360 --> 00:19:10,918
- Oh, good.
- What's the time?

372
00:19:11,120 --> 00:19:12,553
Er, two a. m.

373
00:19:13,280 --> 00:19:15,589
- Good God, what's the crisis?
- No. No crisis.

374
00:19:15,760 --> 00:19:18,991
I'm going through my boxes, and
I knew you'd still be hard at it.

375
00:19:19,400 --> 00:19:22,392
Oh, yes, yes, yes, yes.
Nose to the grindstone.

376
00:19:22,560 --> 00:19:25,518
Well, I've just come across
this Data Base paper.

377
00:19:25,680 --> 00:19:27,671
Oh, you've found...
you've read it!

378
00:19:28,160 --> 00:19:31,072
Thought I'd bettertell you
I'm not happy with it.

379
00:19:31,240 --> 00:19:34,630
You'll welcome an opportunity
to work on something else.

380
00:19:34,800 --> 00:19:38,031
- You didn't mind my calling you?
- No. Not at all Minister.

381
00:19:38,320 --> 00:19:40,197
Always a pleasure
to hearfrom you.

382
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:45,992
I meant to tell him to see me
about it before Cabinet.

383
00:19:46,160 --> 00:19:47,593
Don't ring him now.

384
00:19:48,360 --> 00:19:50,191
You're right, it is a bit late.

385
00:19:51,200 --> 00:19:53,031
Give him anotherten minutes.

386
00:19:58,440 --> 00:20:00,237
If you could be fairly quick.

387
00:20:00,400 --> 00:20:03,039
- He does have Cabinet at 10.
- I can be very quick.

388
00:20:03,200 --> 00:20:06,237
The word "No" is one
of the shortest in the language.

389
00:20:08,120 --> 00:20:11,271
Sorry to be so late.
Lots of reading to do this morning.

390
00:20:11,920 --> 00:20:14,195
Good morning, Bernard.
Thank you, George.

391
00:20:16,160 --> 00:20:18,833
Now, Humphrey, the Data Base.

392
00:20:19,680 --> 00:20:21,477
Have you drafted
yoursafeguards?

393
00:20:21,680 --> 00:20:24,148
Well, Minister,
I quite appreciate your intention

394
00:20:24,320 --> 00:20:26,959
and fully agree
that there is need forsafeguards,

395
00:20:27,120 --> 00:20:28,633
but is this

396
00:20:29,600 --> 00:20:32,717
- the rightway to achieve it?
- Well, it's my way.

397
00:20:33,320 --> 00:20:34,719
One.

398
00:20:36,800 --> 00:20:38,358
That's my decision, anyway.

399
00:20:38,640 --> 00:20:42,394
Well this is not really the time
forall sorts of reasons.

400
00:20:43,680 --> 00:20:45,033
Two.

401
00:20:46,520 --> 00:20:48,033
It's the perfect time.

402
00:20:48,360 --> 00:20:50,715
Safeguards should be developed
alongside systems,

403
00:20:50,880 --> 00:20:52,279
that's common sense.

404
00:20:52,440 --> 00:20:56,558
We tried all this before and
we ran into all sorts of difficulties.

405
00:20:56,800 --> 00:20:57,949
Three.

406
00:20:58,640 --> 00:20:59,789
Such as?

407
00:21:00,680 --> 00:21:03,717
- Well, technical, for instance.
- No. No problems.

408
00:21:03,880 --> 00:21:07,031
We can use the same basicfile
interrogation programme

409
00:21:07,200 --> 00:21:10,158
as the U. S. State Dept. And
the Swedish Ministry of the Interior.

410
00:21:10,600 --> 00:21:11,953
No problems there.

411
00:21:12,320 --> 00:21:15,915
Yes, but there are also formidable
administrative problems.

412
00:21:18,720 --> 00:21:20,711
And all departments are affected.

413
00:21:20,960 --> 00:21:24,669
- An interdepartmental committee...
- No. No. No, Humphrey.

414
00:21:24,880 --> 00:21:28,919
You'll find that the existing
security procedures are adequate.

415
00:21:29,080 --> 00:21:31,833
This is simply an extension.
Anything more?

416
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:35,231
- Well, yes, Minister.
- Legal problems, forexample?

417
00:21:37,840 --> 00:21:39,751
- Yes, Minister.
- Good, good.

418
00:21:39,920 --> 00:21:43,629
- Do we have the legal power?
- I'll answer it. We have.

419
00:21:43,800 --> 00:21:46,792
All personnel affected are bound
by theirstaff agreements.

420
00:21:46,960 --> 00:21:50,509
Yes, but Minister, there will be
a need forextra staffing.

421
00:21:50,680 --> 00:21:54,389
Will you be able to get it
through the parliamentary party?

422
00:21:54,560 --> 00:21:57,313
Yes, I'm quite sure.
Anything further?

423
00:21:57,480 --> 00:21:59,357
I don't think so.
We can go ahead then.

424
00:22:04,360 --> 00:22:05,759
You're very silent.

425
00:22:05,920 --> 00:22:09,799
You don't seem to realise
the amount of work that's involved.

426
00:22:09,960 --> 00:22:12,269
Haven't you examined
safeguards before?

427
00:22:12,440 --> 00:22:13,919
Underanothergovernment?

428
00:22:14,080 --> 00:22:17,755
I remembersome written answers
to parliamentary questions.

429
00:22:18,360 --> 00:22:22,069
Well, in the first place as we've
agreed that question is not...

430
00:22:22,600 --> 00:22:25,558
In the second place,
if there had been investigations,

431
00:22:25,720 --> 00:22:27,995
which there haven't
ornot necessarily,

432
00:22:28,160 --> 00:22:30,628
orl am not at liberty
to say whetherthere have,

433
00:22:30,800 --> 00:22:32,791
there would have been
a project team, which,

434
00:22:32,960 --> 00:22:35,235
had it existed,
on which I cannot comment,

435
00:22:35,400 --> 00:22:37,834
which would nowhave
disbanded if it had existed

436
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:40,070
and the members returned
to do theirdepartments,

437
00:22:40,240 --> 00:22:42,390
if indeed there had been
any such members.

438
00:22:42,880 --> 00:22:44,598
Ornot as the case may be.

439
00:22:45,440 --> 00:22:47,874
- Quite so, Minister.
- I want these safeguards

440
00:22:48,040 --> 00:22:49,837
made available immediately.

441
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:52,355
- Minister, it is not possible.
- It is.

442
00:22:52,520 --> 00:22:54,033
- It isn't.
- It is.

443
00:22:54,200 --> 00:22:55,553
- It isn't.
- It is.

444
00:22:55,720 --> 00:22:58,393
- It isn't.
- 'Tis, 'tis, 'tis, 'tis, 'tis, 'tis.

445
00:22:59,120 --> 00:23:01,680
Just to remind you,
you have Cabinet at 10.00,

446
00:23:01,840 --> 00:23:03,956
the Anglo American Society
at one,

447
00:23:04,120 --> 00:23:07,317
and the "World in Focus"
interview, this evening.

448
00:23:07,560 --> 00:23:10,950
- Can't you get me out of the lunch?
- It's been announced.

449
00:23:11,120 --> 00:23:12,553
I see... I suppose I...

450
00:23:14,320 --> 00:23:16,914
- What's that you just said?
- We can't get out of it.

451
00:23:17,080 --> 00:23:19,310
It's been announced,
it's in the programme.

452
00:23:20,120 --> 00:23:21,519
Thank you, Bernard.

453
00:23:22,640 --> 00:23:24,358
Thank you very much.

454
00:23:24,520 --> 00:23:26,033
Forwhat, Minister?

455
00:23:27,160 --> 00:23:29,515
Foreverything, Bernard.

456
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:43,198
And our Man on the Spot tonight
is the Right HonourableJim Hacker,

457
00:23:43,360 --> 00:23:45,351
MinisterforAdministrative Affairs,

458
00:23:45,520 --> 00:23:48,910
the man at the heart of the Big
Brothercomputercontroversy.

459
00:23:49,360 --> 00:23:51,191
He's talking to Godfrey Finch.

460
00:23:51,360 --> 00:23:54,989
Minister, as you know there's been
an outcry this week about

461
00:23:55,160 --> 00:23:58,869
the dossierthat the Civil Service
bureaucracy has apparently

462
00:23:59,040 --> 00:24:01,918
been building up
on every citizen in this country.

463
00:24:02,080 --> 00:24:06,039
Now, it's rumoured that
this is not in fact, yourown policy,

464
00:24:06,200 --> 00:24:09,590
that you'd like to have safeguards
forthe individual citizen,

465
00:24:09,760 --> 00:24:13,150
but that you are being totally
frustrated at every stage

466
00:24:13,320 --> 00:24:15,834
of the game
by the Civil Service machine.

467
00:24:17,280 --> 00:24:19,236
You know, Godfrey,

468
00:24:20,440 --> 00:24:22,795
there's a lot of nonsence
talked about the Civil Service.

469
00:24:22,960 --> 00:24:26,396
It's a marvellous, efficient,
professional organisation,

470
00:24:26,560 --> 00:24:29,711
capable of enormous energy
and speed.

471
00:24:29,880 --> 00:24:33,316
It's staffed by a lot of talented,
dedicated people

472
00:24:33,600 --> 00:24:36,876
who do everything in theirpower
to help the Government

473
00:24:37,040 --> 00:24:38,712
make it's policies into law.

474
00:24:39,800 --> 00:24:42,553
Well, thank you
forthe commercial, Minister.

475
00:24:43,200 --> 00:24:45,509
Perhaps we can start
the programme now?

476
00:24:45,880 --> 00:24:48,599
The fact of the matter is that
the Civil Service and I

477
00:24:48,760 --> 00:24:51,354
are in complete accord
overthis whole business

478
00:24:52,120 --> 00:24:55,351
and I'm happy to announce
that we're nowready

